{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491609"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:55:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:55:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"997"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/997"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.1,0.05,0.8,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"997"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43920"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/997"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"997"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28902"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1546"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42194"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43920"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a six-month history of a slow growing pigmented lesion on her left ankle (Image). She has a medical history of multiple non-melanoma skin cancers which she has had excised in the General Practice clinic. She takes no regular medications. Suspecting a melanoma, the doctor performs an excisional biopsy. Histology confirms the suspected diagnosis of melanoma and the thickness is reported as 4 mm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sentinel node biopsy","Further excisional biopsy with a 3cm surgical margin","Moh\u0027s surgery","Wide local excision with a 2cm surgical margin and sentinel node biopsy","Immunotherapy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETwo key characteristics in melanoma staging are thickness and ulceration, with greater depth and the presence of ulceration implying more severe disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs per the American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) staging system, a lesion \u0026gt; 2 mm thick is classified as T3 disease and should be managed with \u003Cstrong\u003Ewide local excision with 2cm surgical margin and sentinel node biopsy.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurther excisional biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Eis not required as the histology has confirmed diagnosis. Additionally, a\u003Cstrong\u003E 3 cm surgical margin \u003C/strong\u003Eis insufficient as T3 disease poses a high risk of regional nodal metastasis and must be investigated. There is no evidence to support that surgical margins \u0026gt;2 cm corresponds to improved clinical outcomes. Margins \u0026gt;2 cm have also been associated with longer hospital stays and a higher likelihood of requiring skin grafting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWide local excision is the mainstay of melanoma treatment. \u003Cstrong\u003ESentinel node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E alone will not remove the cancerous tissue that potentially remains.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMoh\u0027s surgery \u003C/strong\u003Eis utilised where tissue sparing is required to minimise the total size of the defect. It is commonly used to treat lentigo maligna or non-melanoma skin cancers involving head and neck distribution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmunotherapy \u003C/strong\u003Ecould be considered by a multidisciplinary team following staging investigations including sentinel node biopsy and imaging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Melanoma thickness and ulceration can be used to determine management and prognosis"],"references":["Keung EZ, Gershenwald JE. The eighth edition American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) melanoma staging system: implications for melanoma treatment and care. Expert Rev Anticancer Ther. 2018;18(8):775-784. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29923435/","Balch CM, Soong S, Ross MI, et al. Long-term results of a multi-institutional randomized trial comparing prognostic factors and surgical results for intermediate thickness melanomas (1.0 to 4.0 mm). Intergroup Melanoma Surgical Trial. Ann Surg Oncol. 2000;7(2):87-97. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10761786/","Balch CM, Urist MM, Karakousis CP, et al. Efficacy of 2-cm surgical margins for intermediate-thickness melanomas (1 to 4 mm). Results of a multi-institutional randomized surgical trial. Ann Surg. 1993;218(3):262-269. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8373269/#:~:text=The%20overall%205%2Dyear%20survival,margins%20(p%20%3C%200.001)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28902"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"997"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16314"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16314"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/46298ba1-eb9d-4d1e-8570-b9fa7ff2ef83.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/46298ba1-eb9d-4d1e-8570-b9fa7ff2ef83.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":443,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRev